title: For Sale:  9mm Croatian PHP MV
postcontent:
For sale is a 9mm PHP MV short-barreled (4") pistol.  This pistol was imported by Century Arms (stamped).  PHP (Prvi Hrvatski Pistolj - first Croatian pistol) is a somewhat strange weapon which was developed in Croatia during its war for independence in early 1990s. Production of this pistol (which was produced in at least two versions, short-barreled PHP MV 9 and long-barreled PHP VM 17) was sporadic, and it was soon replaced in production and use by the more modern HS 2000 pistol.

By design, this pistol represents a mix between Beretta 92 and Walther P38 pistols. The basic short-recoil operated action with vertically tilting locking piece is similar to both pistols, the general appearance of the open-top slide is close to the Walther but the single return spring below the barrel is apparently an Italian influence. Trigger is of traditional double action type, and the safety consists of a manual decocking lever, located on the left side of the grip frame. Magazines are double-stack and hold 15 cartridges.

After purchase, I put about 100 rounds through the pistol and it shoots decent.

The pistol comes in a carrying case (worth about $50), cleaning kit (pictured) and the original manual.  Since this pistol is a bit of an oddity and some even collect these, I'm asking $450 cash for everything.  Bill of Sale.

title: For Sale/Trade:  RELISTED, Proposed Armslist Etiquitte
postcontent:
New Proposed Armslist Etiquette (Just blowing off some steam, laugh with me).

Some of you are already in compliance.  If so, please disregard this update.  If you are not in compliance, please take a few minutes to familiarize yourself with how things work around here.

Because of the varied levels of confusion and miscommunication on this site regarding transactions, I just wanted to take a moment to suggest some rules for making sure everyone has an enjoyable productive experience on this site.  Proposed etiquette rules are as follows:

If you are a seller:

1) You are correct in assuming that you are the superior being in the transaction.  You are doing your fellow man a service and favor by offering your personal belongings up for sale.  Sellers should feel lucky to even receive a return email from you, much less actually engage in negotiations or transactions.

2) Because you are selling an item or items, you are also correct in assuming that the value of said item far exceeds the value that would be assigned in a retail store, pawn shop, or any other public or private market.  Its not ultra-valuable because of what it is, it is ultra-valuable because you’re selling it and you want the most money you can get for it.

3) Even if you have no intention of selling your item or items, and your Blue Book of Gun Values is more than four or five feet away from you, feel free to list your item anyway, making sure to indicate “make offer,” and/or “I’m just seeing what’s out there.”
(This reinforces the superiority of the seller as indicated in Rule #1.  It lets would be buyers know that you do not value money, or time, as you clearly have an abundance of both.)

4)  Referencing Rule #3, you can surely use the “make offer” price to see what people will pay for an item you actually want to sell.  Upon using this feature, feel free to respond to reasonable and low ball offers by becoming “butt hurt,” as you did not indicate the ballpark of what you might want to get out of the item.

5)  Upon becoming “butt hurt,” feel free to employ one of the following methods to cope with the emotional trauma of being so utterly disrespected:

A. Completely ignore the offer, and do not, under any circumstances counter-offer.  This 	may lead to price negotiations. 

B.  If you find yourself in the terrifying grips of negotiations somehow, reply with one or 	two word email/text responses, or more verbose, vague responses.  Be rude.  “Nope,” 	“Looking for more,” and “I’m not sure how much I’d like to sell it for” are all acceptable 	and recommended responses.  

These methods, if properly employed will achieve your ultimate goal of preventing a sale.
Remember, if you sell something, you may then take that money and spend it—This could possibly stimulate the economy:  Something which cannot happen, as Barack Obama will take credit for it.

6)  In the event you do sell something, don’t take your listing down.  In fact, bump the listing as much as you can.  This creates the confusion and frustration that Armslist is all about.

If you are a buyer:  

1)  Remember, Armslist is just like Walmart: you can browse, go to the bathroom, and complain about the ever rising costs of things.  

2)  You should email buyers in one of several ways.  Use whichever is most convenient:
	A.  “I only have 60% of your asking price.  Is that ok?”
	B. “ Will you take (insert lowball offer equivalent to half of what a pawn shop would 	give)?”
	C.  “Do you still have it?” (This is potentially ok, referencing Rule 6 under sellers)
	D.  “I live two and a half hours away—you think you can drive to me?”
*Combining 2A and 2D is particularly effective—however it takes a master negotiator to pull this off.

3)  If the seller messes up and actually responds to your email with something resembling actual negotiation, you should under no circumstances respond in any meaningful way.  At best, you can ignore him/her completely.  If this is impossible, simply use the “buyer communication methods” found under Rule 5, Section B.  However, employing Rule 5, Section B is undesirable, as you may accidently find yourself successfully negotiating.  

4)  Just like Walmart, you can commit to buying things, and then just leave your cart at checkout.  This is achieved in the armslist world by somehow getting a seller to negotiate and agree on a price, only to be saved from a sale by you not showing up.  While the buyer knows he is the superior being, you “stick it to him and show him who’s boss” by not meeting or showing up at a prescribed time and place.

*Remember, as a buyer it is not your job to buy anything, only to waste the time of the seller and annoy him.  This is the male version of “retail therapy” that many women enjoy as they run salespeople around, only to say they’ll “think about it” and not buy anything.  

If you are a trader, things become more difficult.  You must use the rules of both the buyer and seller while avoiding a successful transaction at all costs.  For the novice trader, keep in mind that even if you and the other trader have comparable items, your items are far superior and higher in value, while his trading items must be regarded as having the same value as petting zoo feces.  I hope this helps.

location: Palm Beach, Palm Beach, South Florida
postcontent: Beretta® uses a reliable tilt-breech system on the PX4 Storm Sub-Compact Semi-Auto Pistol to keep it as slim and lightweight as possible, as opposed to the rotating barrel design used on the full-sized PX4 Storm. The tilt-breech system works to dissipate the recoil in the web of the hand and reduce muzzle rise. The PX4 Sub-Compact semi-automatic pistol shoots in either double or single action mode, and is equally suited for concealed carry, home defense, and recreational shooting. The Sub-Compact PX4 Storm features a lightweight, corrosion resistant, fiberglass-reinforced polymer frame that includes an integral Picatinny rail for rapid attachment of tactical lights and laser sights. Interchange backstraps allow a perfect fit to any sized hand; the PX4 Storm has an ambidextrous slide lock and safety, and the magazine release is reversible. The slide has a durable Bruniton™ non-reflective black finish that provides superior corrosion resistance, ideal for concealed carry use where the firearm can be exposed to perspiration on a daily basis. The gun's stainless steel barrel resists corrosion and requires less maintenance. 3-dot sights provide quick target acquisition, and both front and rear sights are dovetailed into the slide, allowing user to easily change them with after market night sights. The Beretta PX4 Storm Sub-Compact Semi-Auto Pistol uses a double-stacked magazine with a hinged baseplate for the pinky, if needed. Full-sized PX4 Storm magazines can also be used with the sub-compact model. Comes with 2 magazines.
